      <body xml:lang="en">
         <div>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="1"
                xml:id="pb-1"
                facs="#i1"/>
            <lb/>
1<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Lecture 2</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">1811</hi>
            <lb/>
The Plan which I propose<lb/>
to adopt in treating of Geology, &amp;<lb/>
which I announced in the introductory<lb/>
Lecture, will I feel, offer much<lb/>
less amusement, than those that are<lb/>
usually followed; -<lb/>
To connect the facts belonging<lb/>
to the mechanism of the Earth, with a<lb/>
general hypothesis of cosmogony, &amp;<lb/>
to make them subservient to speculative<lb/>
views, offers more pleasing associations<lb/>
to the Memory, &amp; more brilliant<lb/>
pictures to the Imagination, than<lb/>
the mere simple development of the<lb/>
real order &amp; existing arrangements<lb/>
of Nature. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="2"
                xml:id="pb-2"
                facs="#i2"/>
            <lb/>
- The phenomena of the external<lb/>
World , as well as the passions &amp;<lb/>
feelings of the human mind, are<lb/>
most impressive, when they are<lb/>
connected <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">by distant</hi> &amp; varied<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">analogies, &amp; tinted</hi> with the<lb/>
brilliant hues of fancy. -<lb/>
- |_ But the end of Science ought<lb/>
to be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Truth</hi>, simple, unadorned<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Truth</hi> &amp; her great object<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Utility</hi>. |_&amp; in the pursuit of<lb/>
Truth, that which was at first<lb/>
a labour, soon becomes a pleasure;<lb/>
for the results are permanent,<lb/>
the effect important, &amp; the delight<lb/>
that the mind receives, constantly<lb/>
increases. - It is neither capricious<lb/>
nor transitory, for it is founded<lb/>
upon the operation of Laws, which<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="3"
                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
are wisely &amp; benevolently constituted,<lb/>
&amp; which are eternal in their operation. -<lb/>
- |_The contemplation of the general<lb/>
exterior of the Earth, shews that even<lb/>
its irregularities are happily disposed.<lb/>
The bleak &amp; elevated Mountain, is<lb/>
contrasted with the <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">sheltered &amp;</add> deep valley.- The<lb/>
shaggy &amp; wooded hill, with the level<lb/>
&amp; cultivated plain - &amp; the bright<lb/>
&amp; even expanse of Sea or Sky, with<lb/>
the deep tinted &amp; unequal Land. -<lb/>
Scenes abound in all parts harmonious;<lb/>
&amp; more delightful, from being warm<lb/>
with animation, &amp; full of the forms<lb/>
of life. - -<lb/>
X<lb/>
- On penetrating beneath the<lb/>
surface, however, a new, &amp; altogether<lb/>
a different order of Things is presented<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
to our attention. All is dark<lb/>
&amp; silent. - Soils, earthy Strata<lb/>
&amp; Rocks are blended together,<lb/>
apparently without symmetry or<lb/>
beauty. Veins of metallic ores,<lb/>
&amp; of crystallized stones intersect<lb/>
them in different directions,<lb/>
&amp; by a transient examination,<lb/>
deformity &amp; disorder only, are<lb/>
perceptible in the subterraneous<lb/>
mineral Kingdom. - -<lb/>
- This effect of confusion,<lb/>
however, soon ceases, in the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">investigating</hi> Mind. - For by<lb/>
continued observation &amp; sagacious<lb/>
comparison, a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">certain arrangement</hi>
            <lb/>
is perceived, even in those<lb/>
rudest of the forms of Matter. -<lb/>
- A distinct analogy appears between<lb/>
their parts, |_ &amp; by their utility &amp; importance<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
2<lb/>
in the general System of Nature, is<lb/>
gradually unfolded, becoming clearer<lb/>
&amp; clearer, till at length it <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">produces</hi>
            <lb/>
full &amp; pleasing conviction. - -<lb/>
- - The orders of Rocks that compose<lb/>
the known part of the surface of the Earth, are<lb/>
very few, &amp; even the species are not<lb/>
numerous; but the varieties are<lb/>
almost infinite. - - -<lb/>
- - The minute study of varieties is<lb/>
however seldom necessary, except<lb/>
in cases, when they are connected<lb/>
with the transition or passage of<lb/>
one species into another. - |_Usually<lb/>
they present the same Characters,<lb/>
speak the same language, tell the<lb/>
same tale. -<lb/>
- - It is upon the distinct outlines<lb/>
in Nature, the marked &amp; well<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
defined differences that Geology<lb/>
truly depends; &amp; for accuracy<lb/>
of Classification &amp; facility of<lb/>
Enquiry, - two kinds of Characters<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">are</del> at least, <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">are</add> required. -<lb/>
- The first Characters are those<lb/>
gained from the minute examination<lb/>
of insulated specimens, from the<lb/>
inherent qualities which belong<lb/>
to the smallest fragment containing<lb/>
all the elements of the Rock. -<lb/>
- The second are the Characters<lb/>
of the Rock considered as<lb/>
a great mass, or as composed<lb/>
of parts, bearing to each other<lb/>
a determinate &amp; ascertainable<lb/>
relation. - - -<lb/>
- In the first series, the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
principal properties to be attended to,<lb/>
are, the figure, &amp; appearance<lb/>
of fracture, the Crystallizations, if<lb/>
any exist, the specific weight, the<lb/>
hardness, &amp; the relation to <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">magnetic</add> Polarity<lb/>
of Electricity, &amp; to the power of<lb/>
conducting heat - to taste, to<lb/>
smell &amp; to touch. -<lb/>
- In insulated Geological<lb/>
Specimens, the natural fractures<lb/>
ought to be preserved, &amp; two<lb/>
new fractures, one parallel to<lb/>
the horizon, &amp; the other perpendicular<lb/>
to it, should be made, &amp; an<lb/>
anciently exposed surface ought<lb/>
to be suffered to remain. -<lb/>
- All this I know, is<lb/>
contrary to the method, of the<lb/>
greater number of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag1" type="person">
          Wernerians
        </name>
            </rs>,<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
who give to their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">specimens however</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">different</hi>, the same square form, &amp;<lb/>
make on every side a new fracture,<lb/>
which answers very well in Mineralogy<lb/>
for Cabinet Specimens, but which in<lb/>
Geology destroys very important<lb/>
indications. For in this <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">instance</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Science</add>
            <lb/>
the specimen ought only to be an assistance<lb/>
to the study of the Rock - And<lb/>
in Rocks, fresh fractures are seldom<lb/>
to be expected; &amp; they present chiefly<lb/>
points, &amp; irregular outlines. -<lb/>
- In examining the fracture of<lb/>
a Rock, if any small irregularities<lb/>
of colour or form appear, the eye<lb/>
should be assisted by a glass |_ and<lb/>
where large but imperfect, ill defined<lb/>
Crystals exist, an attempt should be<lb/>
made to fracture them in the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
3<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">direction</hi> of the parallel &amp; transverse<lb/>
lines, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">which they present</hi>, in order to ascertain<lb/>
if possible, the primitive form. And<lb/>
for the purpose, a common penknife<lb/>
&amp; a small hammer may be used. -<lb/>
- The specific gravity, or the relation<lb/>
of the weight to that of water, may be<lb/>
known by ascertaining what weight of<lb/>
water, a given weight of the fossil will<lb/>
displace. - The <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">magnetic</add> polarity, (if any)<lb/>
may be ascertained by a small needle. -<lb/>
The Electrical power by rubbing the<lb/>
specimen with <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#misc_810"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag2">
          silk
        </term>
            </rs> or by heating it. -<lb/>
The hardness may be judged of by the<lb/>
knife, or by the use of a ring or<lb/>
plate containing a series of stones<lb/>
differing in hardness from the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#chemical_508"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag3">
          diamond
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#chemical_406"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag4">
          Calcareous Spar
          
        </term>
            </rs>. - The other qualities<lb/>
are obvious, &amp; require no elucidation<lb/>
of method. - -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
- In determining the Nature of a<lb/>
particular Rock, a very few Characters<lb/>
usually are adequate; often indeed,<lb/>
a single one is sufficient. -<lb/>
Habitual &amp; attentive observation,<lb/>
will soon enable the Student<lb/>
to catch by a single glance of the<lb/>
eye, or a touch of the hand,<lb/>
the quality, which marks the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">greater number of common Geological</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Species</hi>; &amp; the complication of<lb/>
method is principally necessary<lb/>
only in detecting new varieties. -<lb/>
- <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">I have procured</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">All</add> the Specimens<lb/>
necessary for elucidating the minute<lb/>
Characters of Geology <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">are <add>to be</add> found in the Museum of this Institution<hi rend="superscript">*</hi>
            </add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp;</del> I shall<lb/>
continually have occasion to refer<lb/>
to them, &amp; I shall mention<lb/>
their characteristic properties. -<lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
* Royal Institution<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
On this point unfortunately, no<lb/>
appeal can be made to the senses,<lb/>
at the time of the description, but<lb/>
the bodies <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">themselves may be</add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">have their names affixed</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to them</del>, &amp; maybe examined <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">minutely</add> by<lb/>
those who may consider the study<lb/>
worthy of their attention. -<lb/>
- The study of rocks as Masses<lb/>
require infinitely less preparation, &amp;<lb/>
less detail of minute practices.<lb/>
Each species has an aspect, of a<lb/>
general series of Characters peculiar<lb/>
to itself of which when attentively<lb/>
examined, may in many cases be<lb/>
made, even at considerable distances<lb/>
an accurate indication of its nature.<lb/>
The form of the outline, the colour<lb/>
the interruptions of the surface, the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
lines of the Strata, or blocks, &amp; the<lb/>
magnitude of the projecting or<lb/>
retiring angles; are all amongst<lb/>
the grand external characteristics. -<lb/>
- Instruments are seldom required<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">for assisting</hi> in the discovery of<lb/>
them, And indeed, almost the<lb/>
only ones that can be employed<lb/>
are a pocket telescope, a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <rs xml:id="ttag5" ref="#misc_399" type="miscellaneous">
                  <term xml:id="tag5">
          goniometer
        </term>
               </rs>
            </del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">2 mile <del rend="strikethrough">sect </del> quadrant</add>
            <lb/>
for discovering angles. - a barometer<lb/>
for ascertaining heights &amp; a<lb/>
measuring staff. - - -<lb/>
- The study of the aspect<lb/>
of Rocks, &amp; Mountains is one<lb/>
of the most delightful departments<lb/>
of the Science; &amp; it is constantly<lb/>
connected with the new, the<lb/>
diversified, the beautiful,<lb/>
&amp; the sublime in Nature. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="13"
                xml:id="pb-13"
                facs="#i13"/>
            <lb/>
4<lb/>
- In this Room it can be illustrated by<lb/>
feeble &amp; imperfect sketches only, but<lb/>
these will at least be adequate to<lb/>
exhibit the important facts; they will<lb/>
point out <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">most distinctly</del> the methods,<lb/>
&amp; the nature of the enquiry, &amp;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the arrangements most worthy of</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">being examined</hi>. -<lb/>
- On the point of the aspect of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Rocks &amp; Mountains</hi>, the views<lb/>
of the Geologist, are directed to<lb/>
the same grand objects as those<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Poet &amp; the Printer</hi> - But<lb/>
Science makes <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">distinct</hi> what Taste<lb/>
would require to be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">obscure</hi>;<lb/>
its elements are collected only from<lb/>
the simple &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">permanent</hi>; &amp;<lb/>
it leaves to the arts of imagination,<lb/>
the charms &amp; graces of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">indefinite</hi>
            <lb/>
&amp; the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mutable</hi>. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="14"
                xml:id="pb-14"
                facs="#i14"/>
            <lb/>
- In proceeding to consider our subject -<lb/>
- the arrangement of the Rocks in Nature<lb/>
I shall adopt the division, to which<lb/>
I referred in the last Lecture,<lb/>
into Primary and Secondary. -<lb/>
but to prevent any misconception of<lb/>
the uses of the terms, I shall<lb/>
offer a few observations upon<lb/>
them. - - - -<lb/>
When the word Primitive, or<lb/>
primary, was first adopted by<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#person_305"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="person">
          Lehman
        </name>
            </rs> in the Science, |_ it<lb/>
signified <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the unaltered matter</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the Globe</hi>, <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the matter in which</add> no vestiges of a<lb/>
former order analogous to the<lb/>
existing order of Things were to<lb/>
be found. This meaning, has<lb/>
however gradually been changed,<lb/>
&amp; the term is now <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">usually</del> often,<lb/>
applied to all Rocks that<lb/>
do not contain <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">organic remains</hi>. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
And in consequence, it is often made<lb/>
use of, to denote rocks that abound<lb/>
in fragments derived from the<lb/>
destruction of other Rocks. - Thus<lb/>
it is not uncommon to hear primary<lb/>
Sandstones spoken of. -<lb/>
In this application, I venture<lb/>
to disclaim the use of the words,<lb/>
I shall adhere to the first signification. -<lb/>
Whenever Strata or Rocks, contain<lb/>
any vestiges of destruction or<lb/>
renovation, I shall consider them<lb/>
as Secondary. - &amp; by dividing<lb/>
the two classes into <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">different</add> orders, all<lb/>
the necessary distinctions, may<lb/>
I am convinced, be observed. -<lb/>
- It is but paying a just<lb/>
tribute of respect to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#person_305"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag7" type="person">
          Lehman
        </name>
            </rs>, to<lb/>
whom we owe so much, - that<lb/>
of preserving the purity of his<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
definition - It is greatly of his<lb/>
Glory that 50 years have passed<lb/>
away, of continued progress in<lb/>
the science, &amp; yet his general<lb/>
Classification, still retains<lb/>
all its truth &amp; utility.<lb/>
- Primary rocks are distributed<lb/>
in considerable masses or Strata,<lb/>
&amp; constitute a great part of<lb/>
the known solid matter of the<lb/>
Globe - They are found<lb/>
at the remotest depths below<lb/>
the surface &amp; form by far<lb/>
the greatest portion of the highest<lb/>
Mountain Chains <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">belonging</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to the Globe</del>. -<lb/>
- Of the orders in this<lb/>
Class, the Granitic Rocks,<lb/>
from their position, extent,<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
5.<lb/>
