- In the large masses of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag93"
                ref="#chemical_075"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag93">
          Serpentine
          
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
as they exist in Nature, nothing can<lb/>
exceed the variety of the colours,<lb/>
&amp; the smoothness &amp; polish of the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
surface. - Red , dark green, brown<lb/>
&amp; yellow, all appear; sometimes<lb/>
distinct &amp; sometimes softening into<lb/>
each other, the white foam of the<lb/>
wave, becomes a cause of contrast. -<lb/>
And if <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag94"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag94">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs> is the most sublime<lb/>
of the primitive Rocks in its aspect,<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
