            <lb/>
uniformity &amp; distinctness will be observed<lb/>
in the relationship of the positions of<lb/>
Rocks, &amp; in their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">general arrangement.</hi> -<lb/>
- The chains of primary Rocks,<lb/>
often extending for many hundred<lb/>
miles |_ <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in their</hi> Geographical position,<lb/>
are of considerable importance, in<lb/>
preserving the harmony &amp; order<lb/>
of the great series of Natural<lb/>
Events. -<lb/>
- The Heat of the atmosphere,<lb/>
            <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">lasted</unclear>
            <lb/>
is derived from the agency of<lb/>
the rays of the Sun, on the<lb/>
surface of the Earth, &amp; it<lb/>
diminishes in proportion to the<lb/>
height. - So that in all<lb/>
Seasons, &amp; in all climates,<lb/>
at 2 or 3 miles high, the<lb/>
Air is intensely cold. -<lb/>
- Mountains necessarily partake<lb/>
            <lb/>
